Summary of what changed

    BoardState.board is now int8_t[64] instead of int[64], and a hash field was added. This alone shrinks BoardState from ~276 bytes to ~88 bytes (~3.1x), which reduces the cost of every struct copy in gui_make_move, and shrinks history[MAX_HISTORY] from ~141KB to ~45KB — freeing ~96KB of RAM.
        Fixed a latent bug this change would have caused: gui_init_board's int start[64] array copy via memcpy would have copied the wrong number of bytes into an int8_t[64] board. It's now a static const int8_t start[64].

    Added pin/check caching (PinInfo) and a fast-path legality check (gui_is_legal_move_pins). For the common case — king not in check, moving piece isn't the king, isn't pinned, and isn't an en-passant capture — a pseudo-legal move is accepted as legal without simulating it, skipping the expensive make-move + re-scan-for-attackers step entirely. Castling, en passant, king moves, pinned pieces, and in-check positions always fall back to the fully general slow path for correctness.
        Used in gui_has_legal_moves (was O(4096) worst-case simulations per call — now most of those short-circuit in O(1)), update_selected_destinations, and SAN disambiguation.

    Eliminated duplicate gui_make_move / gui_has_legal_moves calls per move. push_state now computes the resulting position exactly once and hands it back via out_next; gui_move_to_san (renamed gui_move_to_san_ex) reuses that same result instead of recomputing it; and invalidate_and_update_board_caches reuses the already-computed has_legal_moves result via a one-shot hint instead of scanning again immediately afterward.

    Hash-accelerated repetition detection. Each BoardState now carries an FNV-1a hash computed once in gui_make_move/gui_init_board. count_repetitions compares hashes first (O(1) int compare) and only falls back to the full memcmp on an actual hash match, avoiding up to 512 full board comparisons per move.

    Incremental UCI position-command building. trigger_engine_move no longer rebuilds the entire "position startpos moves ..." string from move 1 every single turn — it now appends only new moves since the last sync, and self-heals with a full rebuild if history_count ever goes backwards (Undo/Reset).

    selected_legal_destinations shrunk from int[64] to uint8_t[64] — smaller footprint, cheaper memset.

